<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06345114 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06345114 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  JAPAN; MILITARY; POLICY; LEGISLATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Faced with stiff opposition, the governing Liberal Democrats have given up onefforts this year to pass a bill that would allow Japanese troops to take partin international peacekeeping, party officials said today.;   The bill'spostponement is an embarrassment for the governing party as well as for PrimeMinister Kiichi Miyazawa, who promised after taking office last month to getit passed quickly.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JAPAN TROOP BILL DELAYEDPEACEKEEPING FORCES STALLED  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The bill, which would authorize the dispatch of Japanese troops overseasfor the first time since World War II, passed parliament's lower house but hasbeen stalled by opposition lawmakers in the upper house.;   Officials believethe bill stands a good chance of approval next year but the delay represents ajarring setback for Miyazawa's government at a time when his leadership andintegrity are being questioned.;   &quot;Unfortunately, I don't think you'll findanyone praising Miyazawa's leadership now,&quot; said Yuko Kurihara, a member ofthe prime minister's party faction and a supporter of the troops bill.;   Hesaid that if the bill is eventually scrapped next year Miyazawa's Cabinetmight have to resign.;   Miyazawa became prime minister amid high expectationsabout his expertise in international affairs and ability to exerciseleadership, unlike his predecessor Toshiki Kaifu, who was perceived as apuppet of party power brokers.;   President Bush is to visit Tokyo next month,and the bill's passage would have provided Miyazawa with a fitting response tocriticism that Japan is not pulling its weight in international politics.Japan came under fire for not contributing personnel to the allied forces inthe Persian Gulf war.;   The decision to postpone the measure -- coming 50years almost to the day after Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor -- was a fittingreminder of how little Japan has come to terms with its militarist past.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Tokyo  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911210  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  22E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  294  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, December 10, 199100345114,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>